tigens","Generate memory responses in lymph nodes","Produce IgE antibodies against allergens","Defend mucosal surfaces against pathogens","Mount responses against viral proteins"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of marginal zone B cells is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erespond rapidly to blood-borne polysaccharide antigens\u003C/strong\u003E. These cells are strategically located in the marginal zone of the spleen where they can efficiently encounter and respond to encapsulated bacteria in the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate memory responses in lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E represents the primary function of follicular B cells, while \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduce IgE antibodies against allergens\u003C/strong\u003E describes IgE production mainly associated with plasma cells derived from follicular B cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EDefend mucosal surfaces against pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E characterises the role of B-1 cells and IgA-producing plasma cells, and \u003Cstrong\u003Emount responses against viral proteins\u003C/strong\u003E describes functions mainly performed by follicular B cells and T cells. Marginal zone B cells are particularly important for protecting against encapsulated bacteria due to their ability to quickly respond to polysaccharide antigens without T cell help.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Marginal zone B cells are specialised for rapid responses to blood-borne polysaccharide antigens.","These cells are located in the marginal zone of the spleen where they encounter blood-borne pathogens.","Marginal zone B cells are particularly important for immune responses against encapsulated bacteria."],"references":["Cerutti A, Cols M, Puga I. Marginal zone B cells: virtues of innate-like antibody-producing lymphocytes. Nat Rev Immunol. 2013 Feb;13(2):118-32. doi: 10.1038/nri3383. PMID: 23348416; PMCID: PMC3652659.","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Chapter 9, The Humoral Immune Response. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK10752/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14986"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T17:40:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T17:40:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7674"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115437"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m